Women have long been the creative force behind Native American art, yet their individual contributions have been largely unrecognized, instead treated as anonymous representations of entire cultures. ‘Hearts of Our People: Native Women Artists’ explores the artistic achievements of Native women and establishes their rightful place in the art world.

Video credit: Minneapolis Institute of Art (@artsmia)

@knockhimoutofoffice, a social media voter engagement campaign, features what appears to be a popular piece of boxing training equipment that bears a striking resemblance to Donald Trump. Using the ubiquitous BOB striking dummy as inspiration, artist Alex Esguerra has designed and fabricated a statue representing the frustration many feel about Donald Trump. Using an object intended to withstand ceaseless attacks while remaining unscathed, the artwork underscores the futility of lashing out at Trump and his policies with misdirected rage. 

While it might feel good at the moment to strike a dummy, it will do nothing productive. Esguerra says, “I’ve created the Striking Don as a call to action, a visual way to solicit our strong emotions and channel them to get people out to vote. To actually hit him where it counts. If we all get up, we can truly Knock Him Out of Office.”

Artwork: @esguerrastudio
Produced by: @treborden

node.text:
See the world through Mexican artist Floria González’ (@floriagonzalez) unique eye. 

Floria has been reading about the parallel dimensions, which could well summarize in a theme the whole range of interests she has; the simultaneity of events, the true nature of time, the interconnection of all things in the universe, the influence they have on energy and external matter,the will, intention and individual consciousness. Her interests denote an explorer artist of the true composition of reality and the possibilities of modifying it.

node.title: Through the Lens of an Artist: Florida Gonzalez

node.text:
[2/3] "All my drawings, you always see some kind of surreal scene of optimism but also escapism, which is somewhat of a safe space for myself. My inspiration comes from all sorts of places––it can come from a movie, picture I saw at a train station, sometimes it's just a fleeting thought––and once that idea pops into my mind I start sketching right away. I love that process because I'll never know what the finished product will look like when it starts, so it feels like I'm going on an adventure, discovering the world that I'm creating.

My aim with my work is to bring a sense of joy and curiousity but also a smile to the observer. My work is somewhat like a therapy to me, it's a way to visualize my anxieties and joys, and I always really love adding some humorous elements to my boards just as a reminder to myself and the observer not to take all the little things to heart." - Pop-Surrealist Illustrator Valerie Auersperg (@iamvalerism)

We are looking into the life behind the artwork and focusing on the artist. We will question what's impacted their lives, ranging from their culture, community, creativity, and craft.

node.title: Through the Lens: Pop-Surrealist Illustrator Valerie Auersperg

[2/3] "One of the ways I try to keep the creative juices flowing is to surround myself with backgrounds that I have yet to add something into. I think creativity has a lot to do with the number of inputs we give ourselves, so I try to give myself as many as possible and surround myself with them so that my mind is always thinking about the next piece--before I even start it. That's one of the ways I try to keep artists' block from creeping in."" - Painter Dave Pollot (@davepollotart)

We are looking into the life behind the artwork and focusing on the artist. We will question what's impacted their lives, ranging from their culture, community, creativity, and craft.

node.title: Through the Lens: Painter Dave Pollot

[2/3] "I started to be an artist when I realized that using my creativity was a way of healing my body--literally--from an illness I had some time ago, I think that knowing the history of the many painters that suffered physically and mentally helped me know that what I was doing was actually quite normal. 
Everyone has their own story of pain and suffering, some of which are stigmatized by culture and society. That's also the reason I felt I needed to speak up with the tools I had--the tools of creativity and all the support I had from my family and friends."" - Italian Artist and Illustrator Margherita Paoletti (@margherita_paoletti)

In honor of #Juneteenth and the liberation of slaves in America, we are amplifying artist @sanfordbiggers, whose 2016 #tedtalk remains profoundly relevant today. 
Watch his talk and read more about the artist below. 
video by @ted

Sanford Biggers’ works with historical artefacts, legends and uncomfortable truths. In response to ongoing occurrences of police brutality against Black Americans, Biggers’ BAM series is composed of bronze sculptures recast from fragments of wooden African statues that have been ‘resculpted’. In doing so, Biggers creates hybridized forms that juxtapose classical and historical subjects to create what he calls “future ethnographies”. Sanford Biggers was born in 1970, raised in Los Angeles and currently lives and works in New York City. Biggers' work is in important museum collections such as @themuseumofmodernart, @whitneynyc, @metmuseum, @mocachicago and The National Museum of African American History and Culture in Washington DC, (@nmaahc) among many others.

Each day we'll present one artist, including two of their artworks and a glimpse into their story. Mixed Media Painting: “Gloria’s Trip to Paris” by Johnson Eziefula (@johnsoneziefula) 

“As an artist, I’m particular about self-expression, storytelling, documenting and celebrating the contemporary African, as well as addressing particular contemporary socio-political issues and norms, both domestically, and globally, making use of a psychological and conceptual approach. My works are minimalistic in nature and are characterized by striking depictions of human subjects, at times with conflicting but soothing blend of flat colours, creating highly compelling figurative imagery, with a symbolistic and conceptual basis in emphasis. Therefore; creating a balance and bridging the gap between reality and my imagination. I create art for many reasons, sometimes out of love, pain, fear, anger, frustration and a desire for things to get better. My art comes from a place of optimism and positivity. For me it’s quite a necessity, a learning, expressive and healing process, a subtle means of activism, my custody and getaway at the same time. The society of today is somewhat in a state of dystopia, hence I employ Art as my coping mechanism and as an instrument to voice out, to awaken social consciousness, self-awareness and confer an influence and impact in the littlest way possible to whosoever pays attention, in a quest to achieve my vision of and for a better world.” — Johnson Eziefula (@johnsoneziefula)

Film Photography: “Burnt” by Ben Olive (@_ben.olive_) 

“Without a doubt the most ambitious project I have ever worked on. Shot on Portra 800 pushed to 1600, these images were made over the course of two consecutive shoots using two different couches, as on the first attempt the couch was a lot more flammable than what I was expecting and basically gone within the first five minutes of having lit it. My original vision was also to have the pictures taken at night but after doing this the first time I realized that the flames were a lot brighter than what I had anticipated and only silhouetted everything else around it. We drenched the entire couch with water so that it would burn much slower and also lit it with a lot more daylight to burn through. Fire is unpredictable and deciding to flow with that I also resolved to try pushing film for the first time, not because I necessarily needed to, but more in the hopes of getting some grainy images and nice colour shifts; and also because it was something I had never done before.”

'Cymatic Fountain' cycling between overflow and vibration states by Lachlan Turczan (@lachlanturczan)

"I create works that pose alternatives to today's digitally mediated landscapes. My goal is to make public experiences of natural phenomena that sparks wonder and curiosity in the world around us. With Cymatic Fountain, I've made a gathering space around water much like an outdoor firepit where people can come together to share stories or simply get lost looking at a natural pattern. After a while these tiny wavelets create a disorienting illusion where it feels like you're looking down at an expansive ocean from an airplane window." - Lachlan Turczan (@lachlanturczan)

Turczan is an artist working with water, light and sound. He creates immersive water reflection artworks that have screened at expanded cinema festivals across the United States, most recently at SFMoMA. He also works for WET (@experiencewet) as a choreographer of public spectacles all over the world, from the Singapore Airport's Rain Vortex (@jewelchangiairport) to the largest fountains in Dubai and Las Vegas.
